{"format": "tiptap/v1", "doc": {"type": "doc", "content": [{"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 2}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "What the GPT Family Is"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "The GPT (Generative Pre-trained Transformer) family consists of "}, {"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "decoder-only transformers"}, {"type": "text", "text": " trained with the causal language modelling objective — predict the next token from all previous tokens. Every model in the family shares the same core design: a stack of transformer decoder blocks each containing causal multi-head self-attention followed by a feed-forward network, with pre-layer normalisation and residual connections."}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "The defining characteristic is the "}, {"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "absence of a cross-attention sublayer"}, {"type": "text", "text": ". GPT models have no encoder to attend to — they process a single sequence left-to-right using only causal self-attention. This makes them natural text generators."}]}, {"type": "image", "attrs": {"src": "data:image/svg+xml;base64,", "alt": "GPT decoder-only block (causal attention, FFN, pre-norm, residual) and GPT lineage table from GPT-1 to GPT-4"}}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 2}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "GPT-1: The Template"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "GPT-1 (Radford et al. 2018) introduced the pretraining + fine-tuning paradigm for language models: pretrain a 12-layer transformer on BooksCorpus with causal LM, then fine-tune with a task-specific linear head on labelled data. The architecture was identical to the original transformer's decoder, but without the cross-attention sublayer (no encoder)."}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Key specs: 12 layers, 12 attention heads, d_model = 768, d_ff = 3072, 117M parameters, context 512 tokens."}]}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 2}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "GPT-2: Scaling and Pre-Norm"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "GPT-2 (Radford et al. 2019) scaled to 1.5B parameters and made two architectural changes that became standard for all subsequent large language models:"}]}, {"type": "orderedList", "content": [{"type": "listItem", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Pre-norm"}, {"type": "text", "text": ": LayerNorm is applied "}, {"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "italic"}], "text": "before"}, {"type": "text", "text": " each sublayer rather than after. The block becomes "}, {"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "code"}], "text": "y = x + Sublayer(LN(x))"}, {"type": "text", "text": " instead of "}, {"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "code"}], "text": "y = LN(x + Sublayer(x))"}, {"type": "text", "text": ". Pre-norm stabilises training at scale because the residual stream is never normalised — gradients flow back through the identity skip connection uninhibited."}]}]}, {"type": "listItem", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Final LayerNorm"}, {"type": "text", "text": ": an extra LayerNorm is added after the last transformer block, before the language model head. Without it, the residual stream exiting the last block has unbounded scale."}]}]}, {"type": "listItem", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Residual weight scaling"}, {"type": "text", "text": ": weights of the output projection in each sublayer are initialised at "}, {"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "code"}], "text": "std = 0.02 / sqrt(2 * N_layers)"}, {"type": "text", "text": " to prevent the residual stream from growing with depth."}]}]}]}, {"type": "codeBlock", "attrs": {"language": "python"}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "import torch\nimport torch.nn as nn\nimport math\n\nclass GPT2Block(nn.Module):\n    \"\"\"One GPT-2 decoder block: pre-norm, causal self-attn, FFN, residuals.\"\"\"\n    def __init__(self, d_model, num_heads, d_ff, n_layers):\n        super().__init__()\n        self.ln1  = nn.LayerNorm(d_model)\n        self.attn = nn.MultiheadAttention(d_model, num_heads, batch_first=True)\n        self.ln2  = nn.LayerNorm(d_model)\n        self.ffn  = nn.Sequential(\n            nn.Linear(d_model, d_ff),\n            nn.GELU(),\n            nn.Linear(d_ff, d_model),\n        )\n        # GPT-2 residual-branch weight scaling\n        std = 0.02 / math.sqrt(2 * n_layers)\n        nn.init.normal_(self.attn.out_proj.weight, std=std)\n        nn.init.normal_(self.ffn[-1].weight,        std=std)\n\n    def forward(self, x):\n        T = x.size(1)\n        # Causal mask: lower-triangular (True = attend)\n        mask = torch.tril(torch.ones(T, T, device=x.device)).bool()\n        # Pre-norm + causal self-attention + residual\n        attn_out, _ = self.attn(self.ln1(x), self.ln1(x), self.ln1(x),\n                                attn_mask=~mask)   # MHA expects True = ignore\n        x = x + attn_out\n        # Pre-norm + FFN + residual\n        x = x + self.ffn(self.ln2(x))\n        return x"}]}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 2}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "GPT-3: In-Context Learning"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "GPT-3 (Brown et al. 2020) scaled to 175B parameters and discovered a new capability: "}, {"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "in-context learning"}, {"type": "text", "text": ". By including a few input–output examples directly in the prompt, the model \"learns\" the task without any gradient update. This is possible because the model's attention mechanism can recognise the pattern from the examples and apply it to the new query."}]}, {"type": "codeBlock", "attrs": {"language": "python"}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "# Zero-shot prompting\nzero_shot = \"\"\"\nTranslate English to French:\nThe dog barked loudly. =>\n\"\"\"\n\n# Few-shot prompting (3 examples, then the query)\nfew_shot = \"\"\"\nTranslate English to French:\nThe sun is shining. => Le soleil brille.\nI love coffee. => J'aime le café.\nShe reads every day. => Elle lit tous les jours.\nThe dog barked loudly. =>\n\"\"\"\n# GPT-3 completes: \"Le chien a aboyé bruyamment.\"\n# No fine-tuning needed — examples in context are sufficient.\n\n# Using the OpenAI API (illustrative)\nfrom openai import OpenAI\nclient = OpenAI()\nresponse = client.chat.completions.create(\n    model='gpt-3.5-turbo',\n    messages=[{'role': 'user', 'content': few_shot}]\n)\nprint(response.choices[0].message.content)"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "GPT-3 also used "}, {"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "alternating dense and locally banded sparse attention"}, {"type": "text", "text": " in some layers (inspired by Sparse Transformer) to handle longer contexts, though this detail was not widely publicised and most practical use treats it as a standard transformer."}]}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 2}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "InstructGPT: Aligning with RLHF"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Raw GPT-3 generates plausible next tokens but does not reliably follow instructions. InstructGPT (Ouyang et al. 2022) introduced a three-stage alignment pipeline:"}]}, {"type": "orderedList", "content": [{"type": "listItem", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Supervised fine-tuning (SFT)"}, {"type": "text", "text": ": fine-tune GPT-3 on human-written demonstrations of helpful responses."}]}]}, {"type": "listItem", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Reward model (RM)"}, {"type": "text", "text": ": train a separate model to score responses based on human preference rankings."}]}]}, {"type": "listItem", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Reinforcement learning from human feedback (RLHF)"}, {"type": "text", "text": ": fine-tune the SFT model using PPO, with the RM as the reward signal, to maximise human-rated response quality."}]}]}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "ChatGPT applies this same RLHF pipeline to a GPT-3.5 base model fine-tuned on conversation data."}]}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 2}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Using GPT-2 Locally"}]}, {"type": "codeBlock", "attrs": {"language": "python"}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "from transformers import GPT2LMHeadModel, GPT2Tokenizer\nimport torch\n\ntokenizer = GPT2Tokenizer.from_pretrained('gpt2')\nmodel     = GPT2LMHeadModel.from_pretrained('gpt2')\nmodel.eval()\n\n# Inspect architecture\nprint(model.config)         # n_layer=12, n_head=12, n_embd=768\nprint(sum(p.numel() for p in model.parameters()) / 1e6, 'M')  # 124.4M\n\n# Autoregressive generation\nprompt = \"The transformer architecture was introduced\"\ninputs = tokenizer(prompt, return_tensors='pt')\n\nwith torch.no_grad():\n    output_ids = model.generate(\n        **inputs,\n        max_new_tokens=40,\n        do_sample=True,\n        top_p=0.92,\n        temperature=0.8,\n        pad_token_id=tokenizer.eos_token_id\n    )\n\nprint(tokenizer.decode(output_ids[0], skip_special_tokens=True))\n\n# Access hidden states (useful for embeddings)\nwith torch.no_grad():\n    out = model(**inputs, output_hidden_states=True)\nprint(out.hidden_states[-1].shape)  # (1, T, 768) — last layer hidden states"}]}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 2}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Open-Weight Successors"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "The GPT architecture is the template for virtually every open-weight large language model:"}]}, {"type": "bulletList", "content": [{"type": "listItem", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "LLaMA 1/2/3 (Meta)"}, {"type": "text", "text": ": adds RoPE positional encoding, RMSNorm instead of LayerNorm, SwiGLU FFN, grouped-query attention (GQA) in LLaMA-2/3."}]}]}, {"type": "listItem", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Mistral 7B"}, {"type": "text", "text": ": sliding-window attention (SWA) for local context + GQA for inference efficiency."}]}]}, {"type": "listItem", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Falcon"}, {"type": "text", "text": ": multi-query attention (single KV head); trained on RefinedWeb."}]}]}, {"type": "listItem", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Phi-1/2/3 (Microsoft)"}, {"type": "text", "text": ": small but capable models trained on high-quality synthetic and curated data."}]}]}, {"type": "listItem", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Gemma (Google)"}, {"type": "text", "text": ": RoPE, RMSNorm, GeGLU activation — close to LLaMA architecture."}]}]}]}, {"type": "blockquote", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "The core insight of GPT: "}, {"type": "text", "text": "by training a large enough causal LM on enough text, a single model learns to translate, summarise, answer questions, write code, and reason — all without task-specific training, and all in the same forward pass. Scale transforms a simple next-token predictor into a general-purpose reasoning engine."}]}]}]}}